TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BBOLD Sequences:$EBOLD  A sequence is of the form \[a_1, a_2,
a_3, a_4, \ldots\] where the \(a_n\) are real numbers.  Technically,
a sequence is a function whose domain is the set of natural numbers,
and whose range is a subset of the real numbers.  Sequences may be
defined in various ways:

$BR By $BBOLD listing$EBOLD, and appealing (via the three dots) to your
intuition. Suppose the sequence is \[\frac{1}{2}, \frac{2}{5},
\frac{3}{10}, \frac{4}{17}, \frac{5}{26}, \frac{6}{37}, \ldots \] Then
the \(n\)-th term is 
$BR \(a_n=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}.

$BR $BBOLD Explicitly.$EBOLD  For example, suppose \(a_n=n^n\). Then
\(a_1=\) \{ans_rule(5)\},
\(a_2=\) \{ans_rule(5)\}, and
\(a_3=\) \{ans_rule(5)\}.


$BR $BBOLD Recursively.  $EBOLD  For example, the $BITALIC Fibonacci Sequence$EITALIC is 
defined by
\[a_1 = a_2 = 1,\qquad a_{n+1} = a_n+a_{n-1},\qquad n = 2,3,4,\ldots .\]
Thus
\(a_3=\) \{ans_rule(5)\},
\(a_4=\) \{ans_rule(5)\}, and
\(a_5=\) \{ans_rule(5)\}.


$BR A sequence may or may not have a limit.  For the following
sequences, enter the limit, or enter the letter "D" if the sequence
diverges.

$BR \(a_n = n\qquad\)  \{ans_rule(5)\}.

$BR \(a_n = \frac{1}{n}\qquad\)  \{ans_rule(5)\}.

$BR \(a_n = \frac{n^2+4n-5}{(2n-1)(3n-1)\qquad}\)  \{ans_rule(5)\}.


EOT

$ans = "n/(n^2+1)";
ANS(fun_cmp($ans, limits=>[1,2], vars=>"n"));

ANS(num_cmp(1));
ANS(num_cmp(4));
ANS(num_cmp(27));

ANS(num_cmp(2));
ANS(num_cmp(3));
ANS(num_cmp(5));

ANS(str_cmp(D));
ANS(num_cmp(0));
ANS(num_cmp(1/6));







